        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">‘On the connexion of certain volcanic phænomena’, read 7 March 1838 (<hi rend="italic">Proceedings of the Geological Society</hi> 2 (1833–8): 654–60). The revised version, as published in the <hi rend="italic">Transactions</hi> 5 (1840): 601–31, is reprinted in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1506.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Collected papers</hi></ref> 1: 53–86.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3843.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hopkins 1835</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., p. 41; reproduced in ‘On the connexion of certain volcanic phenomena’, <hi rend="italic">Collected </hi> <hi rend="italic">papers</hi> 1: 77. CD cites both <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3843.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hopkins 1835</ref> and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3844.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hopkins 1836</ref> in support of his own thesis that ‘mountain-chains are formed by a long succession of small movements’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1506.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Collected papers</hi></ref> 1: 73–8).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The title was changed. In the <hi rend="italic">Proceedings of the Geological Society</hi> it reads ‘On the connexion of certain volcanic phænomena, and on the formation of mountain-chains and volcanos, as the effects of continental elevations’. In the <hi rend="italic">Transactions</hi> the paper is entitled ‘On the connexion of certain volcanic phenomena in South America; and on the formation of mountain chains and volcanos, as the effect of the same power by which continents are elevated’.</note>
